				<div class="comment-text">
										<p>See the sources.  I did.  The online etymology one for football, at the end is talking about the first usage in 1881 of Football for the &#8220;American start-stop rugby with padding&#8221; game and not Association Football.  Just look at the context and it&#8217;s clear. </p>
<p>&#8220;The U.S. style (known to some in England as &#8220;stop-start rugby with padding&#8221;) evolved gradually 19c.; the first true collegiate game is considered to have been played Nov. 6, 1869, between Princeton and Rutgers, at Rutgers, but the rules there were more like soccer. A rematch at Princeton Nov. 13, with the home team&#8217;s rules, was true U.S. football. The earliest recorded application of the word football to this is from 1881.&#8221;</p>
				</div>
			
